57 /// Determine whether the given binary operation may overflow.
58 /// Sets \p Result to the value of the operation for BO_Add, BO_Sub, BO_Mul,
59 /// and signed BO_{Div,Rem}. For these opcodes, and for unsigned BO_{Div,Rem},
60 /// the returned overflow check is precise. The returned value is 'true' for
61 /// all other opcodes, to be conservative.
62 bool mayHaveIntegerOverflow(llvm::ConstantInt *LHS, llvm::ConstantInt *RHS,
63  BinaryOperator::Opcode Opcode, bool Signed,
64  llvm::APInt &Result) {
65  // Assume overflow is possible, unless we can prove otherwise.
66  bool Overflow = true;
67  const auto &LHSAP = LHS->getValue();
68  const auto &RHSAP = RHS->getValue();
69  if (Opcode == BO_Add) {
70  Result = Signed ? LHSAP.sadd_ov(RHSAP, Overflow)
71  : LHSAP.uadd_ov(RHSAP, Overflow);
72  } else if (Opcode == BO_Sub) {
73  Result = Signed ? LHSAP.ssub_ov(RHSAP, Overflow)
74  : LHSAP.usub_ov(RHSAP, Overflow);
75  } else if (Opcode == BO_Mul) {
76  Result = Signed ? LHSAP.smul_ov(RHSAP, Overflow)
77  : LHSAP.umul_ov(RHSAP, Overflow);
78  } else if (Opcode == BO_Div || Opcode == BO_Rem) {
79  if (Signed && !RHS->isZero())
80  Result = LHSAP.sdiv_ov(RHSAP, Overflow);
81  else
82  return false;
83  }
84  return Overflow;
85 }
86 
87 struct BinOpInfo {
88  Value *LHS;
89  Value *RHS;
90  QualType Ty; // Computation Type.
91  BinaryOperator::Opcode Opcode; // Opcode of BinOp to perform
92  FPOptions FPFeatures;
93  const Expr *E; // Entire expr, for error unsupported. May not be binop.
94 
95  /// Check if the binop can result in integer overflow.
96  bool mayHaveIntegerOverflow() const {
97  // Without constant input, we can't rule out overflow.
98  auto *LHSCI = dyn_cast<llvm::ConstantInt>(LHS);
99  auto *RHSCI = dyn_cast<llvm::ConstantInt>(RHS);
100  if (!LHSCI || !RHSCI)
101  return true;
102 
103  llvm::APInt Result;
104  return ::mayHaveIntegerOverflow(
105  LHSCI, RHSCI, Opcode, Ty->hasSignedIntegerRepresentation(), Result);
106  }
107 
108  /// Check if the binop computes a division or a remainder.
109  bool isDivremOp() const {
110  return Opcode == BO_Div || Opcode == BO_Rem || Opcode == BO_DivAssign ||
111  Opcode == BO_RemAssign;
112  }
113 
114  /// Check if the binop can result in an integer division by zero.
115  bool mayHaveIntegerDivisionByZero() const {
116  if (isDivremOp())
117  if (auto *CI = dyn_cast<llvm::ConstantInt>(RHS))
118  return CI->isZero();
119  return true;
120  }
121 
122  /// Check if the binop can result in a float division by zero.
123  bool mayHaveFloatDivisionByZero() const {
124  if (isDivremOp())
125  if (auto *CFP = dyn_cast<llvm::ConstantFP>(RHS))
126  return CFP->isZero();
127  return true;
128  }
129 
130  /// Check if at least one operand is a fixed point type. In such cases, this
131  /// operation did not follow usual arithmetic conversion and both operands
132  /// might not be of the same type.
133  bool isFixedPointOp() const {
134  // We cannot simply check the result type since comparison operations return
135  // an int.
136  if (const auto *BinOp = dyn_cast<BinaryOperator>(E)) {
137  QualType LHSType = BinOp->getLHS()->getType();
138  QualType RHSType = BinOp->getRHS()->getType();
139  return LHSType->isFixedPointType() || RHSType->isFixedPointType();
140  }
141  if (const auto *UnOp = dyn_cast<UnaryOperator>(E))
142  return UnOp->getSubExpr()->getType()->isFixedPointType();
143  return false;
144  }
145 };
146 
147 static bool MustVisitNullValue(const Expr *E) {
148  // If a null pointer expression's type is the C++0x nullptr_t, then
149  // it's not necessarily a simple constant and it must be evaluated
150  // for its potential side effects.
151  return E->getType()->isNullPtrType();
152 }
153 
154 /// If \p E is a widened promoted integer, get its base (unpromoted) type.
155 static llvm::Optional<QualType> getUnwidenedIntegerType(const ASTContext &Ctx,
156  const Expr *E) {
157  const Expr *Base = E->IgnoreImpCasts();
158  if (E == Base)
159  return llvm::None;
160 
161  QualType BaseTy = Base->getType();
162  if (!BaseTy->isPromotableIntegerType() ||
163  Ctx.getTypeSize(BaseTy) >= Ctx.getTypeSize(E->getType()))
164  return llvm::None;
165 
166  return BaseTy;
167 }
168 
169 /// Check if \p E is a widened promoted integer.
170 static bool IsWidenedIntegerOp(const ASTContext &Ctx, const Expr *E) {
171  return getUnwidenedIntegerType(Ctx, E).hasValue();
172 }
173 
174 /// Check if we can skip the overflow check for \p Op.
175 static bool CanElideOverflowCheck(const ASTContext &Ctx, const BinOpInfo &Op) {
176  assert((isa<UnaryOperator>(Op.E) || isa<BinaryOperator>(Op.E)) &&
177  "Expected a unary or binary operator");
178 
179  // If the binop has constant inputs and we can prove there is no overflow,
180  // we can elide the overflow check.
181  if (!Op.mayHaveIntegerOverflow())
182  return true;
183 
184  // If a unary op has a widened operand, the op cannot overflow.
185  if (const auto *UO = dyn_cast<UnaryOperator>(Op.E))
186  return !UO->canOverflow();
187 
188  // We usually don't need overflow checks for binops with widened operands.
189  // Multiplication with promoted unsigned operands is a special case.
190  const auto *BO = cast<BinaryOperator>(Op.E);
191  auto OptionalLHSTy = getUnwidenedIntegerType(Ctx, BO->getLHS());
192  if (!OptionalLHSTy)
193  return false;
194 
195  auto OptionalRHSTy = getUnwidenedIntegerType(Ctx, BO->getRHS());
196  if (!OptionalRHSTy)
197  return false;
198 
199  QualType LHSTy = *OptionalLHSTy;
200  QualType RHSTy = *OptionalRHSTy;
201 
202  // This is the simple case: binops without unsigned multiplication, and with
203  // widened operands. No overflow check is needed here.
204  if ((Op.Opcode != BO_Mul && Op.Opcode != BO_MulAssign) ||
205  !LHSTy->isUnsignedIntegerType() || !RHSTy->isUnsignedIntegerType())
206  return true;
207 
208  // For unsigned multiplication the overflow check can be elided if either one
209  // of the unpromoted types are less than half the size of the promoted type.
210  unsigned PromotedSize = Ctx.getTypeSize(Op.E->getType());
211  return (2 * Ctx.getTypeSize(LHSTy)) < PromotedSize ||
212  (2 * Ctx.getTypeSize(RHSTy)) < PromotedSize;
213 }

251  void EmitLValueAlignmentAssumption(const Expr *E, Value *V) {
252  const AlignValueAttr *AVAttr = nullptr;
253  if (const auto *DRE = dyn_cast<DeclRefExpr>(E)) {
254  const ValueDecl *VD = DRE->getDecl();
255 
256  if (VD->getType()->isReferenceType()) {
257  if (const auto *TTy =
258  dyn_cast<TypedefType>(VD->getType().getNonReferenceType()))
259  AVAttr = TTy->getDecl()->getAttr<AlignValueAttr>();
260  } else {
261  // Assumptions for function parameters are emitted at the start of the
262  // function, so there is no need to repeat that here,
263  // unless the alignment-assumption sanitizer is enabled,
264  // then we prefer the assumption over alignment attribute
265  // on IR function param.
266  if (isa<ParmVarDecl>(VD) && !CGF.SanOpts.has(SanitizerKind::Alignment))
267  return;
268 
269  AVAttr = VD->getAttr<AlignValueAttr>();
270  }
271  }
272 
273  if (!AVAttr)
274  if (const auto *TTy =
275  dyn_cast<TypedefType>(E->getType()))
276  AVAttr = TTy->getDecl()->getAttr<AlignValueAttr>();
277 
278  if (!AVAttr)
279  return;
280 
281  Value *AlignmentValue = CGF.EmitScalarExpr(AVAttr->getAlignment());
282  llvm::ConstantInt *AlignmentCI = cast<llvm::ConstantInt>(AlignmentValue);
283  CGF.emitAlignmentAssumption(V, E, AVAttr->getLocation(), AlignmentCI);
284  }
285 
286  /// EmitLoadOfLValue - Given an expression with complex type that represents a
287  /// value l-value, this method emits the address of the l-value, then loads
288  /// and returns the result.
289  Value *EmitLoadOfLValue(const Expr *E) {
290  Value *V = EmitLoadOfLValue(EmitCheckedLValue(E, CodeGenFunction::TCK_Load),
291  E->getExprLoc());
292 
293  EmitLValueAlignmentAssumption(E, V);
294  return V;
295  }

307  /// Known implicit conversion check kinds.
308  /// Keep in sync with the enum of the same name in ubsan_handlers.h
309  enum ImplicitConversionCheckKind : unsigned char {
310  ICCK_IntegerTruncation = 0, // Legacy, was only used by clang 7.
311  ICCK_UnsignedIntegerTruncation = 1,
312  ICCK_SignedIntegerTruncation = 2,
313  ICCK_IntegerSignChange = 3,
314  ICCK_SignedIntegerTruncationOrSignChange = 4,
315  };

317  /// Emit a check that an [implicit] truncation of an integer does not
318  /// discard any bits. It is not UB, so we use the value after truncation.
319  void EmitIntegerTruncationCheck(Value *Src, QualType SrcType, Value *Dst,
320  QualType DstType, SourceLocation Loc);
321 
322  /// Emit a check that an [implicit] conversion of an integer does not change
323  /// the sign of the value. It is not UB, so we use the value after conversion.
324  /// NOTE: Src and Dst may be the exact same value! (point to the same thing)
325  void EmitIntegerSignChangeCheck(Value *Src, QualType SrcType, Value *Dst,
326  QualType DstType, SourceLocation Loc);

328  /// Emit a conversion from the specified type to the specified destination
329  /// type, both of which are LLVM scalar types.
330  struct ScalarConversionOpts {
331  bool TreatBooleanAsSigned;
332  bool EmitImplicitIntegerTruncationChecks;
333  bool EmitImplicitIntegerSignChangeChecks;
334 
335  ScalarConversionOpts()
336  : TreatBooleanAsSigned(false),
337  EmitImplicitIntegerTruncationChecks(false),
338  EmitImplicitIntegerSignChangeChecks(false) {}
339 
340  ScalarConversionOpts(clang::SanitizerSet SanOpts)
341  : TreatBooleanAsSigned(false),
342  EmitImplicitIntegerTruncationChecks(
343  SanOpts.hasOneOf(SanitizerKind::ImplicitIntegerTruncation)),
344  EmitImplicitIntegerSignChangeChecks(
345  SanOpts.has(SanitizerKind::ImplicitIntegerSignChange)) {}
346  };
347  Value *EmitScalarCast(Value *Src, QualType SrcType, QualType DstType,
348  llvm::Type *SrcTy, llvm::Type *DstTy,
349  ScalarConversionOpts Opts);
350  Value *
351  EmitScalarConversion(Value *Src, QualType SrcTy, QualType DstTy,
352  SourceLocation Loc,
353  ScalarConversionOpts Opts = ScalarConversionOpts());
354 
355  /// Convert between either a fixed point and other fixed point or fixed point
356  /// and an integer.

358  SourceLocation Loc);

360  /// Emit a conversion from the specified complex type to the specified
361  /// destination type, where the destination type is an LLVM scalar type.
362  Value *EmitComplexToScalarConversion(CodeGenFunction::ComplexPairTy Src,
363  QualType SrcTy, QualType DstTy,
364  SourceLocation Loc);

366  /// EmitNullValue - Emit a value that corresponds to null for the given type.
367  Value *EmitNullValue(QualType Ty);
368 
369  /// EmitFloatToBoolConversion - Perform an FP to boolean conversion.
370  Value *EmitFloatToBoolConversion(Value *V) {
371  // Compare against 0.0 for fp scalars.
372  llvm::Value *Zero = llvm::Constant::getNullValue(V->getType());
373  return Builder.CreateFCmpUNE(V, Zero, "tobool");
374  }
375 
376  /// EmitPointerToBoolConversion - Perform a pointer to boolean conversion.
377  Value *EmitPointerToBoolConversion(Value *V, QualType QT) {
378  Value *Zero = CGF.CGM.getNullPointer(cast<llvm::PointerType>(V->getType()), QT);
379 
380  return Builder.CreateICmpNE(V, Zero, "tobool");
381  }
382 
383  Value *EmitIntToBoolConversion(Value *V) {
384  // Because of the type rules of C, we often end up computing a
385  // logical value, then zero extending it to int, then wanting it
386  // as a logical value again. Optimize this common case.
387  if (llvm::ZExtInst *ZI = dyn_cast<llvm::ZExtInst>(V)) {
388  if (ZI->getOperand(0)->getType() == Builder.getInt1Ty()) {
389  Value *Result = ZI->getOperand(0);
390  // If there aren't any more uses, zap the instruction to save space.
391  // Note that there can be more uses, for example if this
392  // is the result of an assignment.
393  if (ZI->use_empty())
394  ZI->eraseFromParent();
395  return Result;
396  }
397  }
398 
399  return Builder.CreateIsNotNull(V, "tobool");
400  }

406  Value *Visit(Expr *E) {
407  ApplyDebugLocation DL(CGF, E);

411  Value *VisitStmt(Stmt *S) {
412  S->dump(llvm::errs(), CGF.getContext());
413  llvm_unreachable("Stmt can't have complex result type!");
414  }
415  Value *VisitExpr(Expr *S);
416 
417  Value *VisitConstantExpr(ConstantExpr *E) {
418  // A constant expression of type 'void' generates no code and produces no
419  // value.
420  if (E->getType()->isVoidType())
421  return nullptr;
422 
423  if (Value *Result = ConstantEmitter(CGF).tryEmitConstantExpr(E)) {
424  if (E->isGLValue())
425  return CGF.Builder.CreateLoad(Address(
426  Result, CGF.ConvertTypeForMem(E->getType()),
427  CGF.getContext().getTypeAlignInChars(E->getType())));
428  return Result;
429  }
430  return Visit(E->getSubExpr());
431  }
432  Value *VisitParenExpr(ParenExpr *PE) {
433  return Visit(PE->getSubExpr());
434  }
435  Value *VisitSubstNonTypeTemplateParmExpr(SubstNonTypeTemplateParmExpr *E) {
436  return Visit(E->getReplacement());
437  }
438  Value *VisitGenericSelectionExpr(GenericSelectionExpr *GE) {
439  return Visit(GE->getResultExpr());
440  }
441  Value *VisitCoawaitExpr(CoawaitExpr *S) {
442  return CGF.EmitCoawaitExpr(*S).getScalarVal();
443  }
444  Value *VisitCoyieldExpr(CoyieldExpr *S) {
445  return CGF.EmitCoyieldExpr(*S).getScalarVal();
446  }
447  Value *VisitUnaryCoawait(const UnaryOperator *E) {
448  return Visit(E->getSubExpr());
449  }

532  Value *VisitObjCAvailabilityCheckExpr(ObjCAvailabilityCheckExpr *E) {
533  VersionTuple Version = E->getVersion();
534 
535  // If we're checking for a platform older than our minimum deployment
536  // target, we can fold the check away.
537  if (Version <= CGF.CGM.getTarget().getPlatformMinVersion())
538  return llvm::ConstantInt::get(Builder.getInt1Ty(), 1);
539 
540  return CGF.EmitBuiltinAvailable(Version);
541  }

543  Value *VisitArraySubscriptExpr(ArraySubscriptExpr *E);

549  Value *VisitCompoundLiteralExpr(CompoundLiteralExpr *E) {
550  // Strictly speaking, we shouldn't be calling EmitLoadOfLValue, which
551  // transitively calls EmitCompoundLiteralLValue, here in C++ since compound
552  // literals aren't l-values in C++. We do so simply because that's the
553  // cleanest way to handle compound literals in C++.
554  // See the discussion here: https://reviews.llvm.org/D64464
555  return EmitLoadOfLValue(E);
556  }

575  Value *VisitCallExpr(const CallExpr *E) {

577  return EmitLoadOfLValue(E);

713 
714  // Binary Operators.
715  Value *EmitMul(const BinOpInfo &Ops) {
716  if (Ops.Ty->isSignedIntegerOrEnumerationType()) {
717  switch (CGF.getLangOpts().getSignedOverflowBehavior()) {
718  case LangOptions::SOB_Defined:
719  return Builder.CreateMul(Ops.LHS, Ops.RHS, "mul");
720  case LangOptions::SOB_Undefined:
721  if (!CGF.SanOpts.has(SanitizerKind::SignedIntegerOverflow))
722  return Builder.CreateNSWMul(Ops.LHS, Ops.RHS, "mul");
723  LLVM_FALLTHROUGH;
724  case LangOptions::SOB_Trapping:
725  if (CanElideOverflowCheck(CGF.getContext(), Ops))
726  return Builder.CreateNSWMul(Ops.LHS, Ops.RHS, "mul");
727  return EmitOverflowCheckedBinOp(Ops);
728  }
729  }
730 
731  if (Ops.Ty->isConstantMatrixType()) {
732  llvm::MatrixBuilder MB(Builder);
733  // We need to check the types of the operands of the operator to get the
734  // correct matrix dimensions.
735  auto *BO = cast<BinaryOperator>(Ops.E);
736  auto *LHSMatTy = dyn_cast<ConstantMatrixType>(
737  BO->getLHS()->getType().getCanonicalType());
738  auto *RHSMatTy = dyn_cast<ConstantMatrixType>(
739  BO->getRHS()->getType().getCanonicalType());
740  CodeGenFunction::CGFPOptionsRAII FPOptsRAII(CGF, Ops.FPFeatures);
741  if (LHSMatTy && RHSMatTy)
742  return MB.CreateMatrixMultiply(Ops.LHS, Ops.RHS, LHSMatTy->getNumRows(),
743  LHSMatTy->getNumColumns(),
744  RHSMatTy->getNumColumns());
745  return MB.CreateScalarMultiply(Ops.LHS, Ops.RHS);
746  }
747 
748  if (Ops.Ty->isUnsignedIntegerType() &&
749  CGF.SanOpts.has(SanitizerKind::UnsignedIntegerOverflow) &&
750  !CanElideOverflowCheck(CGF.getContext(), Ops))
751  return EmitOverflowCheckedBinOp(Ops);
752 
753  if (Ops.LHS->getType()->isFPOrFPVectorTy()) {
754  // Preserve the old values
755  CodeGenFunction::CGFPOptionsRAII FPOptsRAII(CGF, Ops.FPFeatures);
756  return Builder.CreateFMul(Ops.LHS, Ops.RHS, "mul");
757  }
758  if (Ops.isFixedPointOp())
759  return EmitFixedPointBinOp(Ops);
760  return Builder.CreateMul(Ops.LHS, Ops.RHS, "mul");
761  }
762  /// Create a binary op that checks for overflow.
763  /// Currently only supports +, - and *.
764  Value *EmitOverflowCheckedBinOp(const BinOpInfo &Ops);
765 
766  // Check for undefined division and modulus behaviors.
767  void EmitUndefinedBehaviorIntegerDivAndRemCheck(const BinOpInfo &Ops,
768  llvm::Value *Zero,bool isDiv);
769  // Common helper for getting how wide LHS of shift is.
770  static Value *GetWidthMinusOneValue(Value* LHS,Value* RHS);
771 
772  // Used for shifting constraints for OpenCL, do mask for powers of 2, URem for
773  // non powers of two.
774  Value *ConstrainShiftValue(Value *LHS, Value *RHS, const Twine &Name);
775 
776  Value *EmitDiv(const BinOpInfo &Ops);
777  Value *EmitRem(const BinOpInfo &Ops);
778  Value *EmitAdd(const BinOpInfo &Ops);
779  Value *EmitSub(const BinOpInfo &Ops);
780  Value *EmitShl(const BinOpInfo &Ops);
781  Value *EmitShr(const BinOpInfo &Ops);
782  Value *EmitAnd(const BinOpInfo &Ops) {
783  return Builder.CreateAnd(Ops.LHS, Ops.RHS, "and");
784  }
785  Value *EmitXor(const BinOpInfo &Ops) {
786  return Builder.CreateXor(Ops.LHS, Ops.RHS, "xor");
787  }
788  Value *EmitOr (const BinOpInfo &Ops) {
789  return Builder.CreateOr(Ops.LHS, Ops.RHS, "or");
790  }
791 
792  // Helper functions for fixed point binary operations.
793  Value *EmitFixedPointBinOp(const BinOpInfo &Ops);
794 
795  BinOpInfo EmitBinOps(const BinaryOperator *E);
796  LValue EmitCompoundAssignLValue(const CompoundAssignOperator *E,
797  Value *(ScalarExprEmitter::*F)(const BinOpInfo &),
798  Value *&Result);
799 
800  Value *EmitCompoundAssign(const CompoundAssignOperator *E,
801  Value *(ScalarExprEmitter::*F)(const BinOpInfo &));

803  // Binary operators and binary compound assignment operators.
804 #define HANDLEBINOP(OP) \
805  Value *VisitBin ## OP(const BinaryOperator *E) { \
806  return Emit ## OP(EmitBinOps(E)); \
807  } \
808  Value *VisitBin ## OP ## Assign(const CompoundAssignOperator *E) { \
809  return EmitCompoundAssign(E, &ScalarExprEmitter::Emit ## OP); \
810  }
811  HANDLEBINOP(Mul)
812  HANDLEBINOP(Div)
813  HANDLEBINOP(Rem)
814  HANDLEBINOP(Add)
815  HANDLEBINOP(Sub)
816  HANDLEBINOP(Shl)
817  HANDLEBINOP(Shr)
818  HANDLEBINOP(And)
819  HANDLEBINOP(Xor)
820  HANDLEBINOP(Or)

822 
823  // Comparisons.
824  Value *EmitCompare(const BinaryOperator *E, llvm::CmpInst::Predicate UICmpOpc,
825  llvm::CmpInst::Predicate SICmpOpc,
826  llvm::CmpInst::Predicate FCmpOpc, bool IsSignaling);
827 #define VISITCOMP(CODE, UI, SI, FP, SIG) \
828  Value *VisitBin##CODE(const BinaryOperator *E) { \
829  return EmitCompare(E, llvm::ICmpInst::UI, llvm::ICmpInst::SI, \
830  llvm::FCmpInst::FP, SIG); }
831  VISITCOMP(LT, ICMP_ULT, ICMP_SLT, FCMP_OLT, true)
832  VISITCOMP(GT, ICMP_UGT, ICMP_SGT, FCMP_OGT, true)
833  VISITCOMP(LE, ICMP_ULE, ICMP_SLE, FCMP_OLE, true)
834  VISITCOMP(GE, ICMP_UGE, ICMP_SGE, FCMP_OGE, true)
835  VISITCOMP(EQ, ICMP_EQ , ICMP_EQ , FCMP_OEQ, false)
836  VISITCOMP(NE, ICMP_NE , ICMP_NE , FCMP_UNE, false)
837 #undef VISITCOMP

878 /// EmitConversionToBool - Convert the specified expression value to a
879 /// boolean (i1) truth value. This is equivalent to "Val != 0".
880 Value *ScalarExprEmitter::EmitConversionToBool(Value *Src, QualType SrcType) {
881  assert(SrcType.isCanonical() && "EmitScalarConversion strips typedefs");
882 
883  if (SrcType->isRealFloatingType())
884  return EmitFloatToBoolConversion(Src);
885 
886  if (const MemberPointerType *MPT = dyn_cast<MemberPointerType>(SrcType))
887  return CGF.CGM.getCXXABI().EmitMemberPointerIsNotNull(CGF, Src, MPT);
888 
889  assert((SrcType->isIntegerType() || isa<llvm::PointerType>(Src->getType())) &&
890  "Unknown scalar type to convert");
891 
892  if (isa<llvm::IntegerType>(Src->getType()))
893  return EmitIntToBoolConversion(Src);
894 
895  assert(isa<llvm::PointerType>(Src->getType()));
896  return EmitPointerToBoolConversion(Src, SrcType);
897 }
898 
899 void ScalarExprEmitter::EmitFloatConversionCheck(
900  Value *OrigSrc, QualType OrigSrcType, Value *Src, QualType SrcType,
901  QualType DstType, llvm::Type *DstTy, SourceLocation Loc) {
902  assert(SrcType->isFloatingType() && "not a conversion from floating point");
903  if (!isa<llvm::IntegerType>(DstTy))
904  return;
905 
906  CodeGenFunction::SanitizerScope SanScope(&CGF);
907  using llvm::APFloat;
908  using llvm::APSInt;
909 
910  llvm::Value *Check = nullptr;
911  const llvm::fltSemantics &SrcSema =
912  CGF.getContext().getFloatTypeSemantics(OrigSrcType);
913 
914  // Floating-point to integer. This has undefined behavior if the source is
915  // +-Inf, NaN, or doesn't fit into the destination type (after truncation
916  // to an integer).
917  unsigned Width = CGF.getContext().getIntWidth(DstType);
918  bool Unsigned = DstType->isUnsignedIntegerOrEnumerationType();
919 
920  APSInt Min = APSInt::getMinValue(Width, Unsigned);
921  APFloat MinSrc(SrcSema, APFloat::uninitialized);
922  if (MinSrc.convertFromAPInt(Min, !Unsigned, APFloat::rmTowardZero) &
923  APFloat::opOverflow)
924  // Don't need an overflow check for lower bound. Just check for
925  // -Inf/NaN.
926  MinSrc = APFloat::getInf(SrcSema, true);
927  else
928  // Find the largest value which is too small to represent (before
929  // truncation toward zero).
930  MinSrc.subtract(APFloat(SrcSema, 1), APFloat::rmTowardNegative);
931 
932  APSInt Max = APSInt::getMaxValue(Width, Unsigned);
933  APFloat MaxSrc(SrcSema, APFloat::uninitialized);
934  if (MaxSrc.convertFromAPInt(Max, !Unsigned, APFloat::rmTowardZero) &
935  APFloat::opOverflow)
936  // Don't need an overflow check for upper bound. Just check for
937  // +Inf/NaN.
938  MaxSrc = APFloat::getInf(SrcSema, false);
939  else
940  // Find the smallest value which is too large to represent (before
941  // truncation toward zero).
942  MaxSrc.add(APFloat(SrcSema, 1), APFloat::rmTowardPositive);
943 
944  // If we're converting from __half, convert the range to float to match
945  // the type of src.
946  if (OrigSrcType->isHalfType()) {
947  const llvm::fltSemantics &Sema =
948  CGF.getContext().getFloatTypeSemantics(SrcType);
949  bool IsInexact;
950  MinSrc.convert(Sema, APFloat::rmTowardZero, &IsInexact);
951  MaxSrc.convert(Sema, APFloat::rmTowardZero, &IsInexact);
952  }
953 
954  llvm::Value *GE =
955  Builder.CreateFCmpOGT(Src, llvm::ConstantFP::get(VMContext, MinSrc));
956  llvm::Value *LE =
957  Builder.CreateFCmpOLT(Src, llvm::ConstantFP::get(VMContext, MaxSrc));
958  Check = Builder.CreateAnd(GE, LE);
959 
960  llvm::Constant *StaticArgs[] = {CGF.EmitCheckSourceLocation(Loc),
961  CGF.EmitCheckTypeDescriptor(OrigSrcType),
962  CGF.EmitCheckTypeDescriptor(DstType)};
963  CGF.EmitCheck(std::make_pair(Check, SanitizerKind::FloatCastOverflow),
964  SanitizerHandler::FloatCastOverflow, StaticArgs, OrigSrc);
965 }
966 
967 // Should be called within CodeGenFunction::SanitizerScope RAII scope.
968 // Returns 'i1 false' when the truncation Src -> Dst was lossy.
969 static std::pair<ScalarExprEmitter::ImplicitConversionCheckKind,
970  std::pair<llvm::Value *, SanitizerMask>>
971 EmitIntegerTruncationCheckHelper(Value *Src, QualType SrcType, Value *Dst,
972  QualType DstType, CGBuilderTy &Builder) {
973  llvm::Type *SrcTy = Src->getType();
974  llvm::Type *DstTy = Dst->getType();
975  (void)DstTy; // Only used in assert()
976 
977  // This should be truncation of integral types.
978  assert(Src != Dst);
979  assert(SrcTy->getScalarSizeInBits() > Dst->getType()->getScalarSizeInBits());
980  assert(isa<llvm::IntegerType>(SrcTy) && isa<llvm::IntegerType>(DstTy) &&
981  "non-integer llvm type");
982 
983  bool SrcSigned = SrcType->isSignedIntegerOrEnumerationType();
984  bool DstSigned = DstType->isSignedIntegerOrEnumerationType();
985 
986  // If both (src and dst) types are unsigned, then it's an unsigned truncation.
987  // Else, it is a signed truncation.
988  ScalarExprEmitter::ImplicitConversionCheckKind Kind;
989  SanitizerMask Mask;
990  if (!SrcSigned && !DstSigned) {
991  Kind = ScalarExprEmitter::ICCK_UnsignedIntegerTruncation;
992  Mask = SanitizerKind::ImplicitUnsignedIntegerTruncation;
993  } else {
994  Kind = ScalarExprEmitter::ICCK_SignedIntegerTruncation;
995  Mask = SanitizerKind::ImplicitSignedIntegerTruncation;
996  }
997 
998  llvm::Value *Check = nullptr;
999  // 1. Extend the truncated value back to the same width as the Src.
1000  Check = Builder.CreateIntCast(Dst, SrcTy, DstSigned, "anyext");
1001  // 2. Equality-compare with the original source value
1002  Check = Builder.CreateICmpEQ(Check, Src, "truncheck");
1003  // If the comparison result is 'i1 false', then the truncation was lossy.
1004  return std::make_pair(Kind, std::make_pair(Check, Mask));
1005 }
1006 
1007 static bool PromotionIsPotentiallyEligibleForImplicitIntegerConversionCheck(
1008  QualType SrcType, QualType DstType) {
1009  return SrcType->isIntegerType() && DstType->isIntegerType();
1010 }
1011 
1012 void ScalarExprEmitter::EmitIntegerTruncationCheck(Value *Src, QualType SrcType,
1013  Value *Dst, QualType DstType,
1014  SourceLocation Loc) {
1015  if (!CGF.SanOpts.hasOneOf(SanitizerKind::ImplicitIntegerTruncation))
1016  return;
1017 
1018  // We only care about int->int conversions here.
1019  // We ignore conversions to/from pointer and/or bool.
1020  if (!PromotionIsPotentiallyEligibleForImplicitIntegerConversionCheck(SrcType,
1021  DstType))
1022  return;
1023 
1024  unsigned SrcBits = Src->getType()->getScalarSizeInBits();
1025  unsigned DstBits = Dst->getType()->getScalarSizeInBits();
1026  // This must be truncation. Else we do not care.
1027  if (SrcBits <= DstBits)
1028  return;
1029 
1030  assert(!DstType->isBooleanType() && "we should not get here with booleans.");
1031 
1032  // If the integer sign change sanitizer is enabled,
1033  // and we are truncating from larger unsigned type to smaller signed type,
1034  // let that next sanitizer deal with it.
1035  bool SrcSigned = SrcType->isSignedIntegerOrEnumerationType();
1036  bool DstSigned = DstType->isSignedIntegerOrEnumerationType();
1037  if (CGF.SanOpts.has(SanitizerKind::ImplicitIntegerSignChange) &&
1038  (!SrcSigned && DstSigned))
1039  return;
1040 
1041  CodeGenFunction::SanitizerScope SanScope(&CGF);
1042 
1043  std::pair<ScalarExprEmitter::ImplicitConversionCheckKind,
1044  std::pair<llvm::Value *, SanitizerMask>>
1045  Check =
1046  EmitIntegerTruncationCheckHelper(Src, SrcType, Dst, DstType, Builder);
1047  // If the comparison result is 'i1 false', then the truncation was lossy.
1048 
1049  // Do we care about this type of truncation?
1050  if (!CGF.SanOpts.has(Check.second.second))
1051  return;
1052 
1053  llvm::Constant *StaticArgs[] = {
1054  CGF.EmitCheckSourceLocation(Loc), CGF.EmitCheckTypeDescriptor(SrcType),
1055  CGF.EmitCheckTypeDescriptor(DstType),
1056  llvm::ConstantInt::get(Builder.getInt8Ty(), Check.first)};
1057  CGF.EmitCheck(Check.second, SanitizerHandler::ImplicitConversion, StaticArgs,
1058  {Src, Dst});
1059 }
1060 
1061 // Should be called within CodeGenFunction::SanitizerScope RAII scope.
1062 // Returns 'i1 false' when the conversion Src -> Dst changed the sign.
1063 static std::pair<ScalarExprEmitter::ImplicitConversionCheckKind,
1064  std::pair<llvm::Value *, SanitizerMask>>
1065 EmitIntegerSignChangeCheckHelper(Value *Src, QualType SrcType, Value *Dst,
1066  QualType DstType, CGBuilderTy &Builder) {
1067  llvm::Type *SrcTy = Src->getType();
1068  llvm::Type *DstTy = Dst->getType();
1069 
1070  assert(isa<llvm::IntegerType>(SrcTy) && isa<llvm::IntegerType>(DstTy) &&
1071  "non-integer llvm type");
1072 
1073  bool SrcSigned = SrcType->isSignedIntegerOrEnumerationType();
1074  bool DstSigned = DstType->isSignedIntegerOrEnumerationType();
1075  (void)SrcSigned; // Only used in assert()
1076  (void)DstSigned; // Only used in assert()
1077  unsigned SrcBits = SrcTy->getScalarSizeInBits();
1078  unsigned DstBits = DstTy->getScalarSizeInBits();
1079  (void)SrcBits; // Only used in assert()
1080  (void)DstBits; // Only used in assert()
1081 
1082  assert(((SrcBits != DstBits) || (SrcSigned != DstSigned)) &&
1083  "either the widths should be different, or the signednesses.");
1084 
1085  // NOTE: zero value is considered to be non-negative.
1086  auto EmitIsNegativeTest = [&Builder](Value *V, QualType VType,
1087  const char *Name) -> Value * {
1088  // Is this value a signed type?
1089  bool VSigned = VType->isSignedIntegerOrEnumerationType();
1090  llvm::Type *VTy = V->getType();
1091  if (!VSigned) {
1092  // If the value is unsigned, then it is never negative.
1093  // FIXME: can we encounter non-scalar VTy here?
1094  return llvm::ConstantInt::getFalse(VTy->getContext());
1095  }
1096  // Get the zero of the same type with which we will be comparing.
1097  llvm::Constant *Zero = llvm::ConstantInt::get(VTy, 0);
1098  // %V.isnegative = icmp slt %V, 0
1099  // I.e is %V *strictly* less than zero, does it have negative value?
1100  return Builder.CreateICmp(llvm::ICmpInst::ICMP_SLT, V, Zero,
1101  llvm::Twine(Name) + "." + V->getName() +
1102  ".negativitycheck");
1103  };
1104 
1105  // 1. Was the old Value negative?
1106  llvm::Value *SrcIsNegative = EmitIsNegativeTest(Src, SrcType, "src");
1107  // 2. Is the new Value negative?
1108  llvm::Value *DstIsNegative = EmitIsNegativeTest(Dst, DstType, "dst");
1109  // 3. Now, was the 'negativity status' preserved during the conversion?
1110  // NOTE: conversion from negative to zero is considered to change the sign.
1111  // (We want to get 'false' when the conversion changed the sign)
1112  // So we should just equality-compare the negativity statuses.
1113  llvm::Value *Check = nullptr;
1114  Check = Builder.CreateICmpEQ(SrcIsNegative, DstIsNegative, "signchangecheck");
1115  // If the comparison result is 'false', then the conversion changed the sign.
1116  return std::make_pair(
1117  ScalarExprEmitter::ICCK_IntegerSignChange,
1118  std::make_pair(Check, SanitizerKind::ImplicitIntegerSignChange));
1119 }
1120 
1121 void ScalarExprEmitter::EmitIntegerSignChangeCheck(Value *Src, QualType SrcType,
1122  Value *Dst, QualType DstType,
1123  SourceLocation Loc) {
1124  if (!CGF.SanOpts.has(SanitizerKind::ImplicitIntegerSignChange))
1125  return;
1126 
1127  llvm::Type *SrcTy = Src->getType();
1128  llvm::Type *DstTy = Dst->getType();
1129 
1130  // We only care about int->int conversions here.
1131  // We ignore conversions to/from pointer and/or bool.
1132  if (!PromotionIsPotentiallyEligibleForImplicitIntegerConversionCheck(SrcType,
1133  DstType))
1134  return;
1135 
1136  bool SrcSigned = SrcType->isSignedIntegerOrEnumerationType();
1137  bool DstSigned = DstType->isSignedIntegerOrEnumerationType();
1138  unsigned SrcBits = SrcTy->getScalarSizeInBits();
1139  unsigned DstBits = DstTy->getScalarSizeInBits();
1140 
1141  // Now, we do not need to emit the check in *all* of the cases.
1142  // We can avoid emitting it in some obvious cases where it would have been
1143  // dropped by the opt passes (instcombine) always anyways.
1144  // If it's a cast between effectively the same type, no check.
1145  // NOTE: this is *not* equivalent to checking the canonical types.
1146  if (SrcSigned == DstSigned && SrcBits == DstBits)
1147  return;
1148  // At least one of the values needs to have signed type.
1149  // If both are unsigned, then obviously, neither of them can be negative.
1150  if (!SrcSigned && !DstSigned)
1151  return;
1152  // If the conversion is to *larger* *signed* type, then no check is needed.
1153  // Because either sign-extension happens (so the sign will remain),
1154  // or zero-extension will happen (the sign bit will be zero.)
1155  if ((DstBits > SrcBits) && DstSigned)
1156  return;
1157  if (CGF.SanOpts.has(SanitizerKind::ImplicitSignedIntegerTruncation) &&
1158  (SrcBits > DstBits) && SrcSigned) {
1159  // If the signed integer truncation sanitizer is enabled,
1160  // and this is a truncation from signed type, then no check is needed.
1161  // Because here sign change check is interchangeable with truncation check.
1162  return;
1163  }
1164  // That's it. We can't rule out any more cases with the data we have.
1165 
1166  CodeGenFunction::SanitizerScope SanScope(&CGF);
1167 
1168  std::pair<ScalarExprEmitter::ImplicitConversionCheckKind,
1169  std::pair<llvm::Value *, SanitizerMask>>
1170  Check;
1171 
1172  // Each of these checks needs to return 'false' when an issue was detected.
1173  ImplicitConversionCheckKind CheckKind;
1174  llvm::SmallVector<std::pair<llvm::Value *, SanitizerMask>, 2> Checks;
1175  // So we can 'and' all the checks together, and still get 'false',
1176  // if at least one of the checks detected an issue.
1177 
1178  Check = EmitIntegerSignChangeCheckHelper(Src, SrcType, Dst, DstType, Builder);
1179  CheckKind = Check.first;
1180  Checks.emplace_back(Check.second);
1181 
1182  if (CGF.SanOpts.has(SanitizerKind::ImplicitSignedIntegerTruncation) &&
1183  (SrcBits > DstBits) && !SrcSigned && DstSigned) {
1184  // If the signed integer truncation sanitizer was enabled,
1185  // and we are truncating from larger unsigned type to smaller signed type,
1186  // let's handle the case we skipped in that check.
1187  Check =
1188  EmitIntegerTruncationCheckHelper(Src, SrcType, Dst, DstType, Builder);
1189  CheckKind = ICCK_SignedIntegerTruncationOrSignChange;
1190  Checks.emplace_back(Check.second);
1191  // If the comparison result is 'i1 false', then the truncation was lossy.
1192  }
1193 
1194  llvm::Constant *StaticArgs[] = {
1195  CGF.EmitCheckSourceLocation(Loc), CGF.EmitCheckTypeDescriptor(SrcType),
1196  CGF.EmitCheckTypeDescriptor(DstType),
1197  llvm::ConstantInt::get(Builder.getInt8Ty(), CheckKind)};
1198  // EmitCheck() will 'and' all the checks together.
1199  CGF.EmitCheck(Checks, SanitizerHandler::ImplicitConversion, StaticArgs,
1200  {Src, Dst});
1201 }
1202 
1203 Value *ScalarExprEmitter::EmitScalarCast(Value *Src, QualType SrcType,
1204  QualType DstType, llvm::Type *SrcTy,
1205  llvm::Type *DstTy,
1206  ScalarConversionOpts Opts) {
1207  // The Element types determine the type of cast to perform.
1208  llvm::Type *SrcElementTy;
1209  llvm::Type *DstElementTy;
1210  QualType SrcElementType;
1211  QualType DstElementType;
1212  if (SrcType->isMatrixType() && DstType->isMatrixType()) {
1213  SrcElementTy = cast<llvm::VectorType>(SrcTy)->getElementType();
1214  DstElementTy = cast<llvm::VectorType>(DstTy)->getElementType();
1215  SrcElementType = SrcType->castAs<MatrixType>()->getElementType();
1216  DstElementType = DstType->castAs<MatrixType>()->getElementType();
1217  } else {
1218  assert(!SrcType->isMatrixType() && !DstType->isMatrixType() &&
1219  "cannot cast between matrix and non-matrix types");
1220  SrcElementTy = SrcTy;
1221  DstElementTy = DstTy;
1222  SrcElementType = SrcType;
1223  DstElementType = DstType;
1224  }
1225 
1226  if (isa<llvm::IntegerType>(SrcElementTy)) {
1227  bool InputSigned = SrcElementType->isSignedIntegerOrEnumerationType();
1228  if (SrcElementType->isBooleanType() && Opts.TreatBooleanAsSigned) {
1229  InputSigned = true;
1230  }
1231 
1232  if (isa<llvm::IntegerType>(DstElementTy))
1233  return Builder.CreateIntCast(Src, DstTy, InputSigned, "conv");
1234  if (InputSigned)
1235  return Builder.CreateSIToFP(Src, DstTy, "conv");
1236  return Builder.CreateUIToFP(Src, DstTy, "conv");
1237  }
1238 
1239  if (isa<llvm::IntegerType>(DstElementTy)) {
1240  assert(SrcElementTy->isFloatingPointTy() && "Unknown real conversion");
1241  bool IsSigned = DstElementType->isSignedIntegerOrEnumerationType();
1242 
1243  // If we can't recognize overflow as undefined behavior, assume that
1244  // overflow saturates. This protects against normal optimizations if we are
1245  // compiling with non-standard FP semantics.
1246  if (!CGF.CGM.getCodeGenOpts().StrictFloatCastOverflow) {
1247  llvm::Intrinsic::ID IID =
1248  IsSigned ? llvm::Intrinsic::fptosi_sat : llvm::Intrinsic::fptoui_sat;
1249  return Builder.CreateCall(CGF.CGM.getIntrinsic(IID, {DstTy, SrcTy}), Src);
1250  }
1251 
1252  if (IsSigned)
1253  return Builder.CreateFPToSI(Src, DstTy, "conv");
1254  return Builder.CreateFPToUI(Src, DstTy, "conv");
1255  }
1256 
1257  if (DstElementTy->getTypeID() < SrcElementTy->getTypeID())
1258  return Builder.CreateFPTrunc(Src, DstTy, "conv");
1259  return Builder.CreateFPExt(Src, DstTy, "conv");
1260 }
1261 
1262 /// Emit a conversion from the specified type to the specified destination type,
1263 /// both of which are LLVM scalar types.
1264 Value *ScalarExprEmitter::EmitScalarConversion(Value *Src, QualType SrcType,
1265  QualType DstType,
1266  SourceLocation Loc,
1267  ScalarConversionOpts Opts) {
1268  // All conversions involving fixed point types should be handled by the
1269  // EmitFixedPoint family functions. This is done to prevent bloating up this
1270  // function more, and although fixed point numbers are represented by
1271  // integers, we do not want to follow any logic that assumes they should be
1272  // treated as integers.
1273  // TODO(leonardchan): When necessary, add another if statement checking for
1274  // conversions to fixed point types from other types.
1275  if (SrcType->isFixedPointType()) {
1276  if (DstType->isBooleanType())
1277  // It is important that we check this before checking if the dest type is
1278  // an integer because booleans are technically integer types.
1279  // We do not need to check the padding bit on unsigned types if unsigned
1280  // padding is enabled because overflow into this bit is undefined
1281  // behavior.
1282  return Builder.CreateIsNotNull(Src, "tobool");
1283  if (DstType->isFixedPointType() || DstType->isIntegerType() ||
1284  DstType->isRealFloatingType())
1285  return EmitFixedPointConversion(Src, SrcType, DstType, Loc);
1286 
1287  llvm_unreachable(
1288  "Unhandled scalar conversion from a fixed point type to another type.");
1289  } else if (DstType->isFixedPointType()) {
1290  if (SrcType->isIntegerType() || SrcType->isRealFloatingType())
1291  // This also includes converting booleans and enums to fixed point types.
1292  return EmitFixedPointConversion(Src, SrcType, DstType, Loc);
1293 
1294  llvm_unreachable(
1295  "Unhandled scalar conversion to a fixed point type from another type.");
1296  }
1297 
1298  QualType NoncanonicalSrcType = SrcType;
1299  QualType NoncanonicalDstType = DstType;
1300 
1301  SrcType = CGF.getContext().getCanonicalType(SrcType);
1302  DstType = CGF.getContext().getCanonicalType(DstType);
1303  if (SrcType == DstType) return Src;
1304 
1305  if (DstType->isVoidType()) return nullptr;
1306 
1307  llvm::Value *OrigSrc = Src;
1308  QualType OrigSrcType = SrcType;
1309  llvm::Type *SrcTy = Src->getType();
1310 
1311  // Handle conversions to bool first, they are special: comparisons against 0.
1312  if (DstType->isBooleanType())
1313  return EmitConversionToBool(Src, SrcType);
1314 
1315  llvm::Type *DstTy = ConvertType(DstType);
1316 
1317  // Cast from half through float if half isn't a native type.
1318  if (SrcType->isHalfType() && !CGF.getContext().getLangOpts().NativeHalfType) {
1319  // Cast to FP using the intrinsic if the half type itself isn't supported.
1320  if (DstTy->isFloatingPointTy()) {
1321  if (CGF.getContext().getTargetInfo().useFP16ConversionIntrinsics())
1322  return Builder.CreateCall(
1323  CGF.CGM.getIntrinsic(llvm::Intrinsic::convert_from_fp16, DstTy),
1324  Src);
1325  } else {
1326  // Cast to other types through float, using either the intrinsic or FPExt,
1327  // depending on whether the half type itself is supported
1328  // (as opposed to operations on half, available with NativeHalfType).
1329  if (CGF.getContext().getTargetInfo().useFP16ConversionIntrinsics()) {
1330  Src = Builder.CreateCall(
1331  CGF.CGM.getIntrinsic(llvm::Intrinsic::convert_from_fp16,
1332  CGF.CGM.FloatTy),
1333  Src);
1334  } else {
1335  Src = Builder.CreateFPExt(Src, CGF.CGM.FloatTy, "conv");
1336  }
1337  SrcType = CGF.getContext().FloatTy;
1338  SrcTy = CGF.FloatTy;
1339  }
1340  }
1341 
1342  // Ignore conversions like int -> uint.
1343  if (SrcTy == DstTy) {
1344  if (Opts.EmitImplicitIntegerSignChangeChecks)
1345  EmitIntegerSignChangeCheck(Src, NoncanonicalSrcType, Src,
1346  NoncanonicalDstType, Loc);
1347 
1348  return Src;
1349  }
1350 
1351  // Handle pointer conversions next: pointers can only be converted to/from
1352  // other pointers and integers. Check for pointer types in terms of LLVM, as
1353  // some native types (like Obj-C id) may map to a pointer type.
1354  if (auto DstPT = dyn_cast<llvm::PointerType>(DstTy)) {
1355  // The source value may be an integer, or a pointer.
1356  if (isa<llvm::PointerType>(SrcTy))
1357  return Builder.CreateBitCast(Src, DstTy, "conv");
1358 
1359  assert(SrcType->isIntegerType() && "Not ptr->ptr or int->ptr conversion?");
1360  // First, convert to the correct width so that we control the kind of
1361  // extension.
1362  llvm::Type *MiddleTy = CGF.CGM.getDataLayout().getIntPtrType(DstPT);
1363  bool InputSigned = SrcType->isSignedIntegerOrEnumerationType();
1364  llvm::Value* IntResult =
1365  Builder.CreateIntCast(Src, MiddleTy, InputSigned, "conv");
1366  // Then, cast to pointer.
1367  return Builder.CreateIntToPtr(IntResult, DstTy, "conv");
1368  }
1369 
1370  if (isa<llvm::PointerType>(SrcTy)) {
1371  // Must be an ptr to int cast.
1372  assert(isa<llvm::IntegerType>(DstTy) && "not ptr->int?");
1373  return Builder.CreatePtrToInt(Src, DstTy, "conv");
1374  }
1375 
1376  // A scalar can be splatted to an extended vector of the same element type
1377  if (DstType->isExtVectorType() && !SrcType->isVectorType()) {
1378  // Sema should add casts to make sure that the source expression's type is
1379  // the same as the vector's element type (sans qualifiers)
1380  assert(DstType->castAs<ExtVectorType>()->getElementType().getTypePtr() ==
1381  SrcType.getTypePtr() &&
1382  "Splatted expr doesn't match with vector element type?");
1383 
1384  // Splat the element across to all elements
1385  unsigned NumElements = cast<llvm::FixedVectorType>(DstTy)->getNumElements();
1386  return Builder.CreateVectorSplat(NumElements, Src, "splat");
1387  }
1388 
1389  if (SrcType->isMatrixType() && DstType->isMatrixType())
1390  return EmitScalarCast(Src, SrcType, DstType, SrcTy, DstTy, Opts);
1391 
1392  if (isa<llvm::VectorType>(SrcTy) || isa<llvm::VectorType>(DstTy)) {
1393  // Allow bitcast from vector to integer/fp of the same size.
1394  unsigned SrcSize = SrcTy->getPrimitiveSizeInBits();
1395  unsigned DstSize = DstTy->getPrimitiveSizeInBits();
1396  if (SrcSize == DstSize)
1397  return Builder.CreateBitCast(Src, DstTy, "conv");
1398 
1399  // Conversions between vectors of different sizes are not allowed except
1400  // when vectors of half are involved. Operations on storage-only half
1401  // vectors require promoting half vector operands to float vectors and
1402  // truncating the result, which is either an int or float vector, to a
1403  // short or half vector.
1404 
1405  // Source and destination are both expected to be vectors.
1406  llvm::Type *SrcElementTy = cast<llvm::VectorType>(SrcTy)->getElementType();
1407  llvm::Type *DstElementTy = cast<llvm::VectorType>(DstTy)->getElementType();
1408  (void)DstElementTy;
1409 
1410  assert(((SrcElementTy->isIntegerTy() &&
1411  DstElementTy->isIntegerTy()) ||
1412  (SrcElementTy->isFloatingPointTy() &&
1413  DstElementTy->isFloatingPointTy())) &&
1414  "unexpected conversion between a floating-point vector and an "
1415  "integer vector");
1416 
1417  // Truncate an i32 vector to an i16 vector.
1418  if (SrcElementTy->isIntegerTy())
1419  return Builder.CreateIntCast(Src, DstTy, false, "conv");
1420 
1421  // Truncate a float vector to a half vector.
1422  if (SrcSize > DstSize)
1423  return Builder.CreateFPTrunc(Src, DstTy, "conv");
1424 
1425  // Promote a half vector to a float vector.
1426  return Builder.CreateFPExt(Src, DstTy, "conv");
1427  }
1428 
1429  // Finally, we have the arithmetic types: real int/float.
1430  Value *Res = nullptr;
1431  llvm::Type *ResTy = DstTy;
1432 
1433  // An overflowing conversion has undefined behavior if either the source type
1434  // or the destination type is a floating-point type. However, we consider the
1435  // range of representable values for all floating-point types to be
1436  // [-inf,+inf], so no overflow can ever happen when the destination type is a
1437  // floating-point type.
1438  if (CGF.SanOpts.has(SanitizerKind::FloatCastOverflow) &&
1439  OrigSrcType->isFloatingType())
1440  EmitFloatConversionCheck(OrigSrc, OrigSrcType, Src, SrcType, DstType, DstTy,
1441  Loc);
1442 
1443  // Cast to half through float if half isn't a native type.
1444  if (DstType->isHalfType() && !CGF.getContext().getLangOpts().NativeHalfType) {
1445  // Make sure we cast in a single step if from another FP type.
1446  if (SrcTy->isFloatingPointTy()) {
1447  // Use the intrinsic if the half type itself isn't supported
1448  // (as opposed to operations on half, available with NativeHalfType).
1449  if (CGF.getContext().getTargetInfo().useFP16ConversionIntrinsics())
1450  return Builder.CreateCall(
1451  CGF.CGM.getIntrinsic(llvm::Intrinsic::convert_to_fp16, SrcTy), Src);
1452  // If the half type is supported, just use an fptrunc.
1453  return Builder.CreateFPTrunc(Src, DstTy);
1454  }
1455  DstTy = CGF.FloatTy;
1456  }
1457 
1458  Res = EmitScalarCast(Src, SrcType, DstType, SrcTy, DstTy, Opts);
1459 
1460  if (DstTy != ResTy) {
1461  if (CGF.getContext().getTargetInfo().useFP16ConversionIntrinsics()) {
1462  assert(ResTy->isIntegerTy(16) && "Only half FP requires extra conversion");
1463  Res = Builder.CreateCall(
1464  CGF.CGM.getIntrinsic(llvm::Intrinsic::convert_to_fp16, CGF.CGM.FloatTy),
1465  Res);
1466  } else {
1467  Res = Builder.CreateFPTrunc(Res, ResTy, "conv");
1468  }
1469  }
1470 
1471  if (Opts.EmitImplicitIntegerTruncationChecks)
1472  EmitIntegerTruncationCheck(Src, NoncanonicalSrcType, Res,
1473  NoncanonicalDstType, Loc);
1474 
1475  if (Opts.EmitImplicitIntegerSignChangeChecks)
1476  EmitIntegerSignChangeCheck(Src, NoncanonicalSrcType, Res,
1477  NoncanonicalDstType, Loc);
1478 
1479  return Res;
1480 }
1481 
1482 Value *ScalarExprEmitter::EmitFixedPointConversion(Value *Src, QualType SrcTy,
1483  QualType DstTy,
1484  SourceLocation Loc) {
1485  llvm::FixedPointBuilder<CGBuilderTy> FPBuilder(Builder);
1486  llvm::Value *Result;
1487  if (SrcTy->isRealFloatingType())
1488  Result = FPBuilder.CreateFloatingToFixed(Src,
1489  CGF.getContext().getFixedPointSemantics(DstTy));
1490  else if (DstTy->isRealFloatingType())
1491  Result = FPBuilder.CreateFixedToFloating(Src,
1492  CGF.getContext().getFixedPointSemantics(SrcTy),
1493  ConvertType(DstTy));
1494  else {
1495  auto SrcFPSema = CGF.getContext().getFixedPointSemantics(SrcTy);
1496  auto DstFPSema = CGF.getContext().getFixedPointSemantics(DstTy);
1497 
1498  if (DstTy->isIntegerType())
1499  Result = FPBuilder.CreateFixedToInteger(Src, SrcFPSema,
1500  DstFPSema.getWidth(),
1501  DstFPSema.isSigned());
1502  else if (SrcTy->isIntegerType())
1503  Result = FPBuilder.CreateIntegerToFixed(Src, SrcFPSema.isSigned(),
1504  DstFPSema);
1505  else
1506  Result = FPBuilder.CreateFixedToFixed(Src, SrcFPSema, DstFPSema);
1507  }
1508  return Result;
1509 }
1510 
1511 /// Emit a conversion from the specified complex type to the specified
1512 /// destination type, where the destination type is an LLVM scalar type.
1513 Value *ScalarExprEmitter::EmitComplexToScalarConversion(
1514  CodeGenFunction::ComplexPairTy Src, QualType SrcTy, QualType DstTy,
1515  SourceLocation Loc) {
1516  // Get the source element type.
1517  SrcTy = SrcTy->castAs<ComplexType>()->getElementType();
1518 
1519  // Handle conversions to bool first, they are special: comparisons against 0.
1520  if (DstTy->isBooleanType()) {
1521  // Complex != 0 -> (Real != 0) | (Imag != 0)
1522  Src.first = EmitScalarConversion(Src.first, SrcTy, DstTy, Loc);
1523  Src.second = EmitScalarConversion(Src.second, SrcTy, DstTy, Loc);
1524  return Builder.CreateOr(Src.first, Src.second, "tobool");
1525  }
1526 
1527  // C99 6.3.1.7p2: "When a value of complex type is converted to a real type,
1528  // the imaginary part of the complex value is discarded and the value of the
1529  // real part is converted according to the conversion rules for the
1530  // corresponding real type.
1531  return EmitScalarConversion(Src.first, SrcTy, DstTy, Loc);
1532 }
1533 
1534 Value *ScalarExprEmitter::EmitNullValue(QualType Ty) {
1535  return CGF.EmitFromMemory(CGF.CGM.EmitNullConstant(Ty), Ty);
1536 }
1537 
1538 /// Emit a sanitization check for the given "binary" operation (which
1539 /// might actually be a unary increment which has been lowered to a binary
1540 /// operation). The check passes if all values in \p Checks (which are \c i1),
1541 /// are \c true.
1542 void ScalarExprEmitter::EmitBinOpCheck(
1543  ArrayRef<std::pair<Value *, SanitizerMask>> Checks, const BinOpInfo &Info) {
1544  assert(CGF.IsSanitizerScope);
1545  SanitizerHandler Check;
1546  SmallVector<llvm::Constant *, 4> StaticData;
1547  SmallVector<llvm::Value *, 2> DynamicData;
1548 
1549  BinaryOperatorKind Opcode = Info.Opcode;
1550  if (BinaryOperator::isCompoundAssignmentOp(Opcode))
1551  Opcode = BinaryOperator::getOpForCompoundAssignment(Opcode);
1552 
1553  StaticData.push_back(CGF.EmitCheckSourceLocation(Info.E->getExprLoc()));
1554  const UnaryOperator *UO = dyn_cast<UnaryOperator>(Info.E);
1555  if (UO && UO->getOpcode() == UO_Minus) {
1556  Check = SanitizerHandler::NegateOverflow;
1557  StaticData.push_back(CGF.EmitCheckTypeDescriptor(UO->getType()));
1558  DynamicData.push_back(Info.RHS);
1559  } else {
1560  if (BinaryOperator::isShiftOp(Opcode)) {
1561  // Shift LHS negative or too large, or RHS out of bounds.
1562  Check = SanitizerHandler::ShiftOutOfBounds;
1563  const BinaryOperator *BO = cast<BinaryOperator>(Info.E);
1564  StaticData.push_back(
1565  CGF.EmitCheckTypeDescriptor(BO->getLHS()->getType()));
1566  StaticData.push_back(
1567  CGF.EmitCheckTypeDescriptor(BO->getRHS()->getType()));
1568  } else if (Opcode == BO_Div || Opcode == BO_Rem) {
1569  // Divide or modulo by zero, or signed overflow (eg INT_MAX / -1).
1570  Check = SanitizerHandler::DivremOverflow;
1571  StaticData.push_back(CGF.EmitCheckTypeDescriptor(Info.Ty));
1572  } else {
1573  // Arithmetic overflow (+, -, *).
1574  switch (Opcode) {
1575  case BO_Add: Check = SanitizerHandler::AddOverflow; break;
1576  case BO_Sub: Check = SanitizerHandler::SubOverflow; break;
1577  case BO_Mul: Check = SanitizerHandler::MulOverflow; break;
1578  default: llvm_unreachable("unexpected opcode for bin op check");
1579  }
1580  StaticData.push_back(CGF.EmitCheckTypeDescriptor(Info.Ty));
1581  }
1582  DynamicData.push_back(Info.LHS);
1583  DynamicData.push_back(Info.RHS);
1584  }
1585 
1586  CGF.EmitCheck(Checks, Check, StaticData, DynamicData);
1587 }
